body:
### Description

OIDC `AccessTokenCredential` and `IdTokenCredential` require `RoutingContext` which prevents the use of either of these tokens for running the background tasks when `RoutingContext` is not available, example:
```
    private void executeUsingOriginalContext(String token) {
        SecurityIdentity originalIdentity = identityAssociation.getIdentity();
        try {
            SecurityIdentity identity = identityProviderManager.authenticateBlocking(
                    new TokenAuthenticationRequest(new AccessTokenCredential(token, 'RoutingContext is required here')));
            identityAssociation.setIdentity(identity);
            // run some task
        } finally {
            identityAssociation.setIdentity(originalIdentity);
        }
    }
```

The reason behind it is that both `AccessTokenCredential` and `IdTokenCredential` extend `OidcTokenCredential` whose only purpose was to carry a `RoutingContext` for `OidcIdentityProvider` to access it, when there was no alternative way of passing `RoutingContext` to `IdentityProvider`.



### Implementation ideas

`OidcTokenCredential` is no longer required as `RoutingContext` can be accessed as an authentication request property and it is also not useful on its own without having to cast it to either `AccessTokenCredential` or `IdTokenCredential` so it should be removed
